            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </table-wrap>
      <p>We use the probability of arbitrary <italic>k</italic>-mers matching, <italic>P</italic>(<italic>k</italic><sub><italic>X</italic></sub> = <italic>k</italic><sub><italic>Y</italic></sub>)<sub><italic>A</italic></sub>, to approximate the probability of <italic>k</italic>-mers matching within a target, <italic>P</italic>(<italic>k</italic><sub><italic>X</italic></sub> = <italic>k</italic><sub><italic>Y</italic></sub>). This is an approximation because the probability of <italic>P</italic>(<italic>k</italic><sub><italic>X</italic> + 1</sub> = <italic>k</italic><sub><italic>Y</italic> + 1</sub>) is known to not be independent of <italic>P</italic>(<italic>k</italic><sub><italic>X</italic></sub> = <italic>k</italic><sub><italic>Y</italic></sub>). However, this approximation approaches equality as <italic>P</italic>(<italic>k</italic><sub><italic>X</italic></sub> = <italic>k</italic><sub><italic>Y</italic></sub>)<sub><italic>A</italic></sub> decreases, which is accomplished by selecting a sufficiently large <italic>k</italic> such that we do not expect to see any arbitrary <italic>k</italic>-mer matches. We suggest using a large enough <italic>k</italic> such that the expected number of intra-target <italic>k</italic>-mer matches is as follows:
