}{}\begin{equation*} \begin{split} P(X = Y)_{H} &amp;= \\ (1 - \varepsilon )^2 &amp;+ (\varepsilon )^2 \cdot P(X_{M} = Y_{M})_{H} \end{split} \end{equation*}\end{document}</tex-math></disp-formula>where <italic>ϵ</italic> is the probability that two homologous bases do not match exactly, and <italic>P</italic>(<italic>X</italic><sub><italic>M</italic></sub> = <italic>Y</italic><sub><italic>M</italic></sub>)<sub><italic>H</italic></sub> is the probability that two homologous bases both mutate to the same base. The default probability of <italic>ϵ</italic> is 0.01. We assume that when the homologous bases do not match, the observed base is dependent on the GC-content of the environment. Let λ be the GC-content of the environment. The probability of <italic>P</italic>(<italic>X</italic><sub><italic>M</italic></sub> = <italic>Y</italic><sub><italic>M</italic></sub>)<sub><italic>H</italic></sub> is defined as follows:
